//meridianstar.com/2025/12/03/sheriffs-department-announces-december-sobriety-checkpoints/', '2025-12-09 09:20:32+00', null, 'fc8f2633-c41d-4f7b-b893-25d7d4d822c5'), ('22', 'CA', 'Kern', 'Kern', 'Highway 11/80 and Butts Rd.', 'Lauderdale County sheriff’s deputies will be looking for impaired drivers heading into the holidays after the Sheriff’s Department announced a series of sobriety checkpoints will be set up throughout the county over the next few weeks.     The department is required to announce checkpoints ahead of time if the main goal will be to check for impaired drivers. Safety checkpoints, where deputies check for seat belts, insurance and drivers’ licenses, do not have to be publicized in advance.
', '2025-12-15', '9:30 PM PST', 'https://meridianstar.com/2025/12/03/sheriffs-department-announces-december-sobriety-checkpoints/', '2025-12-09 09:24:07+00', null, '4a1d5f1f-c67b-42f4-bc73-686a056de470'), ('23', 'CA', 'Santa Cruz', 'Santa Cruz ', 'Ocean St corridor.', '*Santa Cruz Police to Conduct DUI Checkpoint*
On Friday, December 12th, 2025, from 10pm to 2am, the Santa Cruz Police Department will be conducting a “Driving Under the Influence” (DUI) sobriety checkpoint on the Ocean St corridor.  Funding for this checkpoint is provided to the Santa Cruz Police Department by a state grant furnished by the California Office of Traffic Safety.
Officers will be contacting drivers passing through the checkpoint for signs of alcohol and/or drug impairment and will strive to only delay motorists momentarily.  Drivers caught driving impaired can expect possible arrest, license suspension, and insurance increases, as well as fines, fees, DUI classes, and other expenses that can exceed $10,000.
The primary purpose of a DUI Checkpoint is to increase awareness, deter impaired driving and to arrest those drivers who are found to be under the influence.  The checkpoint is being held to continue the Santa Cruz Police Department’s commitment to public safety in our community and to remove impaired drivers from our roadways.
The Santa Cruz Police Department urges the community to report DUI drivers by calling 911.', '2025-12-12', '10pm- 2am PST', 'https://www.facebook.com/santacruzpolice/posts/santa-cruz-police-to-conduct-dui-checkpointon-friday-december-12th-2025-from-10p/1287459643410776/', '2025-12-09 09:27:17+00', null, 'cc4a09f0-04ad-45f6-b562-5fa95339dd23'), ('24', 'CA', 'Los Angeles', 'South Pasadena', 'Undisclosed location', 'South Pasadena, Calif. – On December 27, 2025, the South Pasadena Police Department will conduct a driving under the influence (DUI) Checkpoint from 7:00 p.m. to 2:00 a.m. at an undisclosed location within the city.

DUI checkpoint locations are determined based on data showing incidents of impaired driving-related crashes. The primary purpose of DUI checkpoints is to promote public safety by taking suspected impaired drivers off the road..

“Impaired drivers put others on the road at significant risk,” Acting Police Chief Shannon Robledo said. “Any prevention measures that reduce the number of impaired drivers on our roads significantly improve traffic safety.”

The South Pasadena Police Department reminds the public that impaired driving is not just from alcohol. Some prescription medications and over-the-counter drugs may interfere with driving. While medicinal and recreational marijuana are legal, driving under the influence of marijuana is illegal.', '2025-12-27', '7pm-2am PST', 'https://www.southpasadenaca.gov/News-articles/12.17.2025-South-Pasadena-Police-Department-to-Hold-DUI-Checkpoint-December-27?utm_source=chatgpt.com', '2025-12-23 03:46:32.717286+00', null, '610a6a56-53ee-4a33-bee8-6fcc6a9463e7'), ('25', 'CA', 'San Francisco', 'San Francisco', 'undisclosed location', 'The San Francisco Police Department’s Traffic Unit will be conducting a DUI checkpoint patrol Saturday, December 27th, 2025, between the hours of 7:00 P.M. and 3:00 A.M. This checkpoint is a part of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration’s (NHTSA) national Winter campaign, “Drive Sober or Get Pulled Over”. The holiday season can be dangerous for people on the road. The goal of the campaign is to stop suspected impaired drivers who put others at risk. Research shows that crashes involving an impaired driver can be reduced by up to 20 percent when well-publicized DUI checkpoints and proactive DUI patrols are conducted routinely.

Officers will be looking for signs of alcohol and/or drug impairment. When possible, specially trained officers will be available to evaluate those suspected of drug-impaired driving.  Recent statistics reveal that 30 percent of drivers in fatal crashes had one or more drugs in their systems.  A study of active drivers showed more tested positive for drugs that may impair driving (14 percent) than did for alcohol (7.3 percent). Of the drugs, marijuana was most prevalent, at 7.4 percent, slightly more than alcohol.

Drivers who are caught driving impaired can expect the impact of a DUI arrest to include jail time, fines, fees, DUI classes, and other expenses that can exceed $10,000, not to mention the embarrassment when friends and family find out.

SFPD encourages everyone to celebrate the holiday season responsibly and make this a safe holiday season for everyone on the road. Funding for this saturation is provided to the San Francisco Police Department by a grant from the California Office of Traffic Safety, through the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, reminding everyone to ‘Report Drunk Drivers – Call 9-1-1.', '2025-12-27', '7pm - 3am PST', 'https://www.sanfranciscopolice.org/news/sfpd-conduct-dui-checkpoint-december-27th-2025-25-157?fbclid=IwY2xjawO1zqhleHRuA2FlbQIxMABicmlkETEzS0o2OFVjVXBKaWxrdU1ac3J0YwZhcHBfaWQQMjIyMDM5MTc4ODIwMDg5MgABHqpM9VLxsTndAsM_Ty_tQdjiejztHWiv_1miScfmdP2cY8iSX_BoAnWEMDYa_aem_byhDKctZLHZUryw9XUsmig', '2025-12-23 03:48:29+00', null, '252d8103-0ce8-4fac-8e6e-a2b29c7d77b5'), ('26', 'CA', 'Marin', 'San Rafael', 'undisclosed location', 'San Rafael, CA. – On Friday, January 30th, 2026, the San Rafael Police Department will conduct a driving under the influence (DUI) Checkpoint on January 30th, 2026, from 5:00 pm to 1:00 am at an undisclosed location in the southern area of San Rafael.

DUI checkpoint locations are determined based on data showing the locations of impaired-driving-related crashes. The primary purpose of DUI checkpoints is to promote public safety by taking suspected impaired drivers off the road.

“Impaired drivers put others on the road at significant risk,” Sergeant Mathis said. “Any prevention measures that reduce the number of impaired drivers on our roads significantly improve traffic safety.”

The San Rafael Police Department reminds the public that impaired driving is not just from alcohol. Some prescription medications and over-the-counter drugs may interfere with driving. While medicinal and recreational marijuana are legal, driving under the influence of marijuana is illegal.

Drivers charged with a first-time DUI face an average of $13,500 in fines and penalties, as well as a suspended license.

Funding for this program was provided by a grant from the California Office of Traffic Safety, through the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.', '2026-01-30', '5pm - 1am PST', 'https://www.srpd.org/press-release.php?id=835&utm_source=chatgpt.com', '2025-12-23 03:57:34+00', null, '84e1b898-cfa2-467c-8ec9-7d5c978dcab7'), ('27', 'CA', 'Los Angeles', 'San Marino', 'Undisclosed location', null, '2025-12-27', '8pm-2am PST', 'https://sanmarinoca.gov/news_detail_T34_R679.php?utm_source', '2025-12-25 04:31:23+00', null, '81c8c5d5-54bb-4918-9e91-a91a49028bd3'), ('28', 'CA', 'Contra Costa', 'Pinole', 'Undisclosed location', 'The Pinole Police Department Traffic Unit will set up a DUI and driver’s license checkpoint on Saturday, Dec. 27 at 1333 San Pablo Ave. The checkpoint will run from 8:30 p.m. to 2:30 a.m. to help keep roads safe during the holiday weekend. 

Officers will briefly stop drivers to check for signs of alcohol or drug impairment and to make sure drivers have a valid license. Motorists should expect only short delays. Trained officers will also be on hand to evaluate drivers suspected of being impaired by drugs, which are an increasing factor in crashes.

The department says checkpoints like this help deter impaired driving and reduce crashes. From Jan. 1, 2023, through Nov. 30, 2025, Pinole police responded to 382 traffic collisions, including 70 with injuries and one fatal crash. Of those, 44 crashes involved impaired drivers, and officers made 59 DUI arrests during the same period. ', '2025-12-27', '8:30pm-2:20am PST', 'https://richmondstandard.com/richmond/2025/12/22/pinole-police-to-hold-dui-checkpoint-on-dec-27/', '2025-12-25 04:37:10+00', null, 'de178bd8-ab94-4d13-ad3f-a6a38f67ab40'), ('29', 'CA', 'Fresno', null, 'undisclosed location.', 'On December 20, 2025, 14 people were arrested for DUI at a DUI checkpoint. The DUI checkpoint was he…', '2025-12-27', 'not specified', 'https://www.facebook.com/watch/?v=626692760504897', '2025-12-25 04:39:37+00', null, 'e12c76cd-a54c-489f-9176-3b2f269a879c'), ('30', 'CA', 'Contra Costa', 'Martinez-area', ' within Contra Costa County', 'SOBRIETY AND DRIVER LICENSE CHECKPOINT

MARTINEZ, CA – The California Highway Patrol (CHP), Contra Costa Area will be conducting a sobriety and driver license checkpoint on December 26, 2025, within Contra Costa County.

The goal of the CHP is to ensure the safe passage of each and every motorist by targeting roads where there is high frequency of intoxicated or unlicensed drivers. A sobriety and driver license checkpoint is a proven effective tool for achieving this goal and is designed to augment existing patrol operations.

Funding for this sobriety checkpoint was provided by a grant from the California Office of Traffic Safety, through the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
', '2025-12-26', 'undisclosed time', 'https://www.facebook.com/photo/?fbid=1284236230398715&set=a.300612565427758', '2026-01-01 05:05:16.01503+00', null, '52d65f83-2feb-4b8b-afb5-47cd38fcf41b'), ('31', 'CA', 'Kern', 'Desert Hot Spring', 'undisclosed location', '
The Desert Hot Springs Police Department will conduct a DUI Checkpoint on December 26, 2025, at an undisclosed location within the city.

Driving under the influence of alcohol or drugs puts lives at risk and carries serious consequences, including:

• Driver’s license suspension
• Fines and court fees
• Vehicle Towed
• Possible jail time

Plan ahead — designate a sober driver, use a rideshare, or call a friend. Making the right choice can save lives.

Our goal is public safety, not citations. Help us keep our community safe for everyone.', '2025-12-26', 'undisclosed time', 'https://www.facebook.com/photo?fbid=1316930207145265&set=a.302453935259569', '2026-01-01 05:09:05.044275+00', null, '2e5b82ba-0de6-40f7-a988-0aa5713c7a64'), ('32', 'CA', 'San diego', 'Atherton', 'El Camino Real, Middlefield Road and Alameda de Las Pulgas. ', 'OCEANSIDE, CA — A Driver’s License/Driving Under the Influence (DUI) Checkpoint will be facilitated by the Oceanside Police Department at an undisclosed location in the City of Oceanside on Friday, December 12th, from 6 p.m. to 2 a.m. on Saturday, December 13th.

DUI checkpoint locations are determined based on data showing incidents of impaired-driving crashes. The primary purpose of DUI checkpoints is to promote public safety by removing drivers suspected of DUI from the roadway while also educating non-impaired motorists about the dangers of driving under the influence of alcohol and/or drugs. Officers will also ensure motorists passing through the checkpoint are properly licensed.

Although DUI incidents are commonly associated with alcohol, many prescription medications can also impair a driver. While a limited amount of cannabis (marijuana) is legal for adults 21 years and older to possess, it remains unlawful to drive while under the influence of cannabis. Motorists driving under the influence of any combination of drugs and/or alcohol are subject to arrest.

Drivers charged with a first-time DUI face an average of $13,500 in fines and penalties, as well as a suspended license.

Funding for this program was provided by a grant from the California Office of Traffic Safety, through the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.

